{"questionId":"14620047","questionHtml":"<p>Find the coordinates of the points on the curve&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;where&nbsp; the gradient is zero.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to use chain rule to find&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp;(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> &nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>…</mo></math></strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Coordinates are&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Special case: For two correct coordinate pairs award <em><strong>(M1)A1(M1)A0A1</strong></em>. For extra coordinate pairs award <em><strong>(M1)A1(M1)A1A0</strong></em>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong><em>[5 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"14620047","referenceCode":"23N.1.AHL.TZ1.11a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the coordinates of the points on the curve y=fx where the gradient is zero.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.3—Graphing"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}